segments.text: Hey everyone, this is Jane, and I'm super excited to talk about today's topic, models.
Don't worry, I'm not talking about those fashion models you see on TV.
I mean role models, amazing people who have already done something great that you want to do too.
They're like your own superheroes, guiding you to success.
What's a role model and why should you care?
So, a role model is someone who's already crushed it at what you're aiming for.
Want to dominate basketball?
Maybe Shaquille O'Neal or Michael Jordan is your guy, or both.
These are people who've been there, done that, and you can totally learn from them.
Why does this matter?
Because it's like a shortcut to success.
You don't have to stumble through every mistake yourself.
By checking out what they did right and wrong, you can level up fast.
Like, superhero fast.
Let me hit you with a quick story.
When I kicked off my own business, I was totally lost.
Zero clue what I was doing.
I was just an English teacher.
I could have winged it, messed up a ton, and figured it out the hard way.
But who's got time for that?
I wanted to win sooner.
So, I hung.
Hunted down role models, people who were already bosses in business.
I devoured their books, hit up their seminars, soaked in all their wisdom,
and then used their tricks for my own gig.
And guess what?
I made it happen way faster.
It was like borrowing years of their grind and turning it into weeks for me.
How this works for English.
How this works for English.
You can do the exact same thing with English.
Or anything.
Find people who are absolute champs at learning languages and swipe their best moves.
It's not copying.
It's being smart.
These role models help you learn quicker, dodge dumb mistakes, and feel unstoppable.
Plus, seeing them nail it proves you can, too.
Back when I started teaching English, I was a hot mess.
I had a social work degree.
I had a job.
I had a degree.
Not a teaching one.

A few students were zooming ahead of everyone else.
I was like, what's their deal?
So, I grilled them, asked tons of questions, and started seeing patterns.
Later, when I got my master's in teaching English,
I dove into research.
And found out the science matched what my top students were doing.
That's when it clicked.
And I built the effortless English system from real people and real results.
Check out these rock star role models.
Let me hook you up with some of my all-star students and their secrets.
Jeannie from Korea.
This girl was a listening ninja.
She had her iPod blasting my lessons and my lessons.
I was a little nervous.
I was like, what's going on?

Steve Kaufman.

Hundreds.

How to score your own role models.
So, where do you find these epic role models?
The Internet's your goldmine.
You can link up with superstar English learners from anywhere.
Forums, blogs, or groups like the Effortless English Club.
These are your people, your crew, who are on the same vibe, smashing the same goals.

They've got your back, share killer tips, and lift you up when you're dragging.
Going solo is rough.

Your mission?
Build your team.

Track down your role models and assemble your crew.
Hunt for people who are slaying English.

Do this.
